terizing it as \"a potential bonanza for America's richest real estate investors.\"\n\nAs the financial website Motley Fool explains, \"Depreciation can dramatically reduce taxable income on rental profits.\" Under current tax law, a married couple can already apply up to $500,000 in depreciation -- the gradual, IRS-determined cost of maintaining a property -- to their tax bill. The stimulus package lifts that cap for a three-year period.\n\n\"It's a pretty big deal,\" Peter Buell, of the accounting firm Marcum, told The Times. And it benefits the top 1% of taxpayers, making an existing aspect of tax law into a windfall, for some.\n\nAs The Times notes, Jared Kushner, President Donald Trump's son-in-law, was able to avoid paying any taxes in 2018 by applying on-paper, if not actually realized, losses from ample property investments.", "source": {"uri": "businessinsider.com", "dataType": "news", "title": "Business Insider"}, "authors": [{"uri": "charles_davis@businessinsider.com", "name": "Charles Davis", "type": "author", "isAgency": false}], "concepts": [{"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depreciation", "type": "wiki", "score": 5, "label": {"eng": "Depreciation"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_estate", "type": "wiki", "score": 5, "label": {"eng": "Real estate"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_New_York_Times", "type": "org", "score": 5, "label": {"eng": "The New York Times"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accounting", "type": "wiki", "score": 4, "label": {"eng": "Accounting"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Recovery_and_Reinvestment_Act_of_2009", "type": "wiki", "score": 4, "label": {"eng": "American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business_Insider", "type": "wiki", "score": 4, "label": {"eng": "Business Insider"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internal_Revenue_Service", "type": "org", "score": 4, "label": {"eng": "Internal Revenue Service"}}, {"uri": "htt